- `zone.js` version: 0.10.3
- reproduce repo: https://github.com/JiaLiPassion/zone-promise-seq

The code will look like this.
```
<html>
  <script src="./node_modules/zone.js/dist/zone-evergreen.js"></script>
  <script>
    const promise = Promise.resolve(1);
    function doSomethingWithoutZoneTask() {
      window[Zone.__symbol__('requestAnimationFrame')](() => {
        console.log('handler begin');
        promise.then(() => {
          console.log('promise then called');
        });
        div.removeChild(btn);
        console.log('handler end');
      });
    }
    window.onload = function() {
      const btn = document.getElementById('btn');
      const div = document.getElementById('div');
      btn.addEventListener('blur', () => {
        console.log('blur');
      });
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
        doSomethingWithoutZoneTask();
      });
    }
  </script>
  <body>
    <div id="div">
      <button id="btn">Test</button>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
```

And when user click button `Test`, the output in the console will be

```
handler begin
blur
promise then called
handler end
```

So the `promise.then` callback is being executed synchronize which is not correct.

The reason is here https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/master/packages/zone.js/lib/zone.ts#L1283, and it seems this issue is a known issue, since there is a test case here, https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/master/packages/zone.js/test/browser/element.spec.ts#L73

so in some cases, the `drainMicroTaskQueue` will be invoked synchronize, we should always use `native promsie` to schedule a microTask to run `drainMicroTaskQueue`.

In Angular with ViewEngine a destroyed view can't be interacted with (ex. one can't trigger change detection on such views). With ivy it is possible to call methods on a destroyed view and there is no error message / logs indicating that a view was destroyed.

Here is [the test exposing difference in VE vs. ivy behaviour](https://github.com/pkozlowski-opensource/angular/commit/e972be659827be252fec3b6c20c4986161de253c):

```typescript
it('should prevent usage of a destroyed fixture', () => {
    @Component({selector: 'test-cmpt', template: ``})
    class TestCmpt {
    }

    TestBed.configureTestingModule({declarations: [TestCmpt]});
    const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(TestCmpt);

    fixture.destroy();

    expect(() => {fixture.detectChanges()})
        .toThrowError(/Attempt to use a destroyed view: detectChanges/);
  });
```

# üêû bug report

> Note: This bug report is specifically for IE11.


### Affected Package
I believe it would be @angular/core? It would be whatever handles transpiling for ES5. I am using 8.2.14 at the moment.


### Is this a regression?
I don't know as this is the first version I have used.

### Description
If I use the object notation on an element using [ngClass] like so:

`<ul [ngClass]="{'hidden': activeLoc}">`

`activeLoc` is a number in my case. In some cases it is undefined.

IE 11 reports a very vague error saying `Object expected` and after I dug around in the stack trace it pointed to this function in vendor-es5.js on line 82596 (I know that line number will be different for other folk). This error causes the rest of the application not to work by the way.

```
    function iterateListLike$1(obj, fn) {
      if (Array.isArray(obj)) {
        for (var i = 0; i < obj.length; i++) {
          fn(obj[i]);
        }
      } else {
        /** @type {?} */
        var iterator = obj[getSymbolIterator()]();
        /** @type {?} */

        var item;

        while (!(item = iterator.next()).done) {
          fn(item.value);
        }
      }
    }
```
I ended up adding a console log in this vendor file to see what `obj` was and the stack trace in IE11 was an object with a 'hidden': undefined property in it. The fix for me was to use a ternary function. After I did this and rebuilt, the error went away in IE 11.

`<ul [ngClass]="(activeLoc) ? 'hidden' : ''">`


